1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 4. Be2 {The 'Wuss', a
solid but unambitious variation that you are likely to encounter quite often
in practice.} 4... Bxe2 5. Qxe2 Qxd5 6. Nf3 e6 7. O-O Bd6 8. c4 Qh5 $1 {
Threatening ...Bxh2+.} 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. h3 O-O-O $1 {Opposite-sided castling is
a feature of the Wuss variation, and also the best way for Black to liven up
proceedings. The game now turns into an attacking race, and Black already has
running shoes on.} 11. Be3 g5 $5 {Points for attitude, but objectively Black
should have first prepared this by ...Rhg8, with excellent chances. I can only
imagine White's reaction to this second outrageous pawn sacrifice in the first
eleven moves of the game.} 12. Nxg5 Qg6 13. Qf3 $6 (13. Nf3 $1 Rhg8 14. Nh4 Qg7
{gives Black a dangerous initiative on the kingside, but White should have
chanced this defensive approach.}) 13... Bb4 $1 14. Rfd1 $2 {Black's courage
is rewarded.} ({Better was} 14. Nce4 $1 Be7 $1 {with excellent compensation
for Black.}) 14... Bxc3 15. bxc3 h6 $1 {Suddenly, White's knight is short on
squares.} 16. d5 Ne5 17. Qe2 hxg5 18. Bxa7 Qf5 19. Rab1 Ne4 ({Already winning
on material, Damaso could have appropriately crowned his historic outing for 3
...Bg4 with the explosive} 19... Rxh3 $3 20. gxh3 Rh8 $1 {with an unparryable
attack.}) 20. Bd4 g4 $1 21. Qb2 b6 22. Qa3 gxh3 23. Bxb6 Nf3+ 24. Kf1 ({Or} 24.
gxf3 h2+ 25. Kg2 Qh3+ 26. Kh1 Qxf3#) 24... hxg2+ 25. Ke2 Ng3+ $1 {These
knights have had quite a day out. And one of them will soon produce a rather
unexpected reincarnation...} 26. fxg3 Qe4+ 27. Be3 g1=N+ $3 {He's back!} 28.
Kf1 Qxc4+ 29. Kg2 Rh2# {Perhaps now you can appreciate why this game is
credited with sparking the 3...Bg4 craze!} 0-1

