1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. c4 e6 $1 4. dxe6 Bxe6 5. d4 $6 {The most natural move,
but not the best. White underestimates the speed at which the black forces
will develop.} (5. Nf3 {is the main line, after which I recommend Black
continue with} Qe7 $1 6. Qe2 Nc6 7. d4 Bf5 $1 {, with excellent compensation.})
5... Bb4+ 6. Bd2 (6. Nc3 Ne4 $1 {is also uncomfortable for White.}) 6... Qe7 7.
Bxb4 ({White should have preferred returning the pawn with the tamer} 7. Be2 {
, although presumably White was still out to punish Black for such impudence
in the opening.} Ne4 8. Nf3 Nxd2 9. Nbxd2 Bxc4 {is equal.}) 7... Qxb4+ 8. Qd2
(8. Nd2 $6 Nc6 $1 9. d5 ({or} 9. Ngf3 $2 O-O-O 10. d5 Nxd5 $1 {and wins}) 9...
O-O-O $1 {leaves Black with an incredibly strong attack.}) 8... Nc6 9. Nc3 $2 (
{White's only chance was to walk the tightrope after} 9. d5 O-O-O $1 10. Nc3 $1
{and now Black can unleash the powerful novelty} Ne5 $3 {, after which White
remains in big trouble.}) 9... O-O-O $5 (9... Bxc4 $1 {was simple and strong;
Black has a clear advantage. However, Hodgson is known for hunting the big
game, and simply regathering his pawn wasn't on his radar.}) 10. d5 Bg4 {The
bishop finds its way to our favourite square after all, preparing to bring the
final rook into the attack along the e-file. While the text is objectively not
strongest, it certainly presents White with the most opportunities to go wrong.
} ({As we saw in the note to White's eighth move,} 10... Ne5 $3 {is a valuable
and unplayed improvement.}) 11. f3 Rhe8+ 12. Be2 Bf5 13. O-O-O $1 {The only
chance, although White's king remains desperately short of air.} Na5 {The
black pieces create a menacing force around the white queenside. Several
threats are in the air, including the cute ...Qb3 followed by ...Qxa2 and ...
Nb3 mate.} 14. g4 $6 (14. Nb5 $2 {loses brilliantly to} Rxe2 $3 15. Nxe2 ({or}
15. Qxb4 Rc2+ 16. Kb1 Rxc4+) 15... Qxc4+ 16. Qc3 Qxb5 17. Nd4 Qxd5 {with a
decisive material advantage.}) (14. b3 $1 {was White's only hope. Despite an
imposing position, it's not clear how Black can break down White's defences,
although} c6 $5 {is probably a good place to start.}) 14... Bg6 $6 (14... Nxc4
$1 15. Bxc4 Qxc4 16. gxf5 Nxd5 $1 {was the clearest route, threatening the
deadly ...Ne3. It requires some deep and precise calculation, but there aren't
many branches to consider. After the forced} 17. Qd4 Qc6 18. Qa4 {Black can
simply swap down to a winning endgame with} Nxc3 19. Rxd8+ Kxd8 $1 20. Qxc6
Nxa2+ 21. Kb1 Re1+ 22. Kxa2 bxc6 {. Despite having an extra piece, White's
forces are completely helpless.}) 15. Nh3 $6 (15. b3 $1 {was again White's
only resource, after which} c6 $1 {is unclear.}) 15... Nd7 $6 {Another
inaccuracy, but one can certainly understand the cute idea that tempted
Hodgson into this relocation.} (15... Nxc4 {is clearly better for Black.}) 16.
Nb1 $4 (16. Ne4 $1 {was White's only try, blocking off the sharp-shooting
black bishop. White has good chances to escape the onslaught.}) 16... Qb3 $1 {
Very nice. It's all over.} 17. Bd3 Qxa2 $1 18. Qb4 Re2 $1 19. Bxe2 Nb3+ 20.
Qxb3 Qxb3 21. Rd2 Qe3 0-1

