1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 $5 4. f3 $1 {Kevin, a noted theoretician,
plays in the most principled fashion. If Black decides to throw opening
principles to the wind and sacrifice a pawn from the get-go, surely White can
just take it - right?} Bf5 5. Bb5+ Nbd7 6. c4 e6 $1 7. dxe6 Bxe6 8. d5 Bf5 9.
Nc3 Bc5 {One of five viable alternatives for Black's ninth move. Black's bishops cast an impressive duo
with their control of their symmetric diagonals.} 10. Qe2+ Kf8 $5 (10... Qe7 {
is the very sound alternative. Black's initiative extends into the queenless
middlegame.}) 11. g4 $2 {Continuing in an aggressive fashion, but running into
a violent refutation.} Nxg4 $3 12. fxg4 Qh4+ 13. Kd1 $2 (13. Kf1 $4 Bd3 $1 {
wins the white queen.}) (13. Kd2 $1 {is White's best chance, although} Bxg4 14.
Nf3 Qh6+ 15. Kc2 Qg6+ 16. Kb3 c6 $1 {leaves Black with a commanding attack.})
13... Bxg4 14. Bxd7 $1 {The best practical try.} ({If} 14. Nf3 Qh5 15. Rf1 Ne5
$1 {wins back the piece with interest.}) 14... Bxe2+ 15. Ngxe2 {White has
enough material for the queen, at least for the time being. The real problem
is that the white king remains perilously exposed. Black must continue to pile
on the pressure without allowing White any respite.} Rd8 $1 16. Bf5 Qxc4 17.
Kc2 Rxd5 18. Rf1 Bb4 19. Be3 (19. Be6 $4 {loses to} Qd3+ 20. Kb3 Bxc3 $1) 19...
Re5 20. Rf4 Qc6 21. Be4 $1 Qe8 $1 {These two players represent the new wave of
very strong tacticians coming out of Asian chess, and in this game they don't
disappoint. Laylo has snatched a bunch of pawns, but the black kingside is
undeveloped and vulnerable, while the white forces are beginning to look
threatening for the first time in the game. Black is still clearly better, but
this is the sort of sharp position that can turn on a dime.} 22. Bd4 Re6 23.
Rg1 (23. Raf1 $1 {was more testing.}) 23... f6 24. Bd3 Bd6 $1 25. Rfg4 c5 $1
26. Bf2 g5 $1 {Very precise! Laylo finds the most accurate means of defence -
pushing forward. Black's extra pawns do a great job of barricading the
kingside.} 27. h4 h5 28. Re4 (28. Ra4 $1 g4 29. Rd1 $1 {would have given White
more chances.}) 28... g4 29. Ng3 Bxg3 30. Bxc5+ $2 {Losing, but the
alternatives weren't too attractive.} ({For example,} 30. Bxg3 Rxe4 31. Bxe4 (
31. Nxe4 $4 c4 $1 {wins a piece}) 31... Kg7 {leaves Black's king surprisingly
safe behind his wall of foot soldiers. Meanwhile, the black pawns on the
queenside are ready to launch their own assault. Black should win with a
certain degree of care.}) 30... Kg7 31. Rxg3 Rxe4 32. Bxe4 Qe5 $1 {White's
pieces are unfortunately placed and cannot all be defended.} 33. Bf2 Qf4 34.
Rg2 Rc8 $1 35. Bxb7 ({Or} 35. Kd3 Rd8+ 36. Bd4 Rxd4+ $1 37. Kxd4 f5 {and wins.}
) 35... Rc7 36. Ba8 Qa4+ $1 37. Kb1 Qe8 $1 {A cute finish.} ({If} 37... Qe8 38.
Bd5 {, then} Rxc3 39. bxc3 Qb5+ {wins the bishop.}) 0-1

