1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 4. f3 Bf5 5. c4 e6 6. dxe6 (6. g4 $2 {an unfortunate attempt to
transpose into the Correspondence Refutation, but it really doesn't work here:}
Nxg4 $3 7. fxg4 Qh4+ 8. Kd2 (8. Ke2 $4 Bxg4+ 9. Nf3 Bxf3+ 10. Kxf3 Qh5+ {wins
the queen}) 8... Be4 9. Nf3 Qf2+ {and Black is clearly better.}) (6. Nc3 exd5
7. g4 Be6 $1 {is very promising for Black.}) (6. Qb3 $6 exd5 $1 7. Qxb7 Nbd7 8.
c5 Bxc5 {gives Black a decisive attack. For example,} 9. dxc5 Rb8 $3 10. Qxa7
O-O 11. Qa3 Qe7+ 12. Ne2 Nxc5 $1 {and White's king will not survive much
longer, because} 13. Kf2 Bxb1 $1 14. Rxb1 Nce4+ $1 {leads to a winning endgame
for Black.}) 6... Nc6 $1 {This is the position that inspired me, and I'm sure
many other club players, to take up the Portuguese. Black shows a complete
disregard for material, initiating this double pawn sacrifice to prioritize
rapid development. Engines already evaluate our compensation as being
completely sufficient, Black has a tremendous score in practical play, and
you're actually likely to get it about once in every 25 outings against 1 e4.
