standard treatment.} 11. Kxe3 Bc2 $3 {the strongest and definitely the
prettiest, but it's worth noting the two other ways Black could win, as they
represent common tactical motifs for this variation:} (11... Qe7+ 12. Kf2 Nxd4
$1 13. Qxd4 Bc5 {wins the queen}) (11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Qe7+ 13. Kd2 Rd8 {is
another way to pick up the dame}) 12. Qd2 Ng4+ $3 13. fxg4 ({or} 13. Kf4 Bd6+
14. Kxg4 Bf5+ $1 15. Kxf5 Qh4 {and mate in two} 16. g4 Re8 17. d5 g6#) 13... Qg5+ {0-1 Ge.Sergeev-D.
Saulin, Tula 2005.}) 9... Re8 10. a3 (10. Ne2 Rxe3 $3 {(you should be getting
used to this by now!)} 11. Kxe3 Qe7+ (11... Nxd4) ({and} 11... Ne5 $5 {also win
}) 12. Kf2 Re8 13. Qb3 Nxd4 $1 14. Nxd4 Qe1+ 15. Kg1 Bc5 {and mate in nine
more moves.}) 10... Rxe3 11. Kxe3 (11. axb4 Rd3 $3 {finishes the game.}) 11...
Qe7+ $2 {Black had a choice of attractive wins; I failed to find the most
convincing continuation.} (11... Be1 $3 {, delivering mate in 18 (!), was
definitely the most aesthetic finisher. Just gorgeous.}) (11... Nxd4) ({and}
11... Bc5 {were also winning swiftly.}) 12. Kf2 Re8 13. g3 $2 (13. Be2 $1 {
would make Black's conversion attempts somewhat problematic, although the
attack is still very powerful.}) 13... Qe3+ 14. Kg2 Be1 $3 {Another common
theme to remember.} 15. Nh3 Nxd4 16. Nc3 Nxf3 $1 17. Be2 Nh4+ {Mate follows.}
0-1

