{This game is one of early 'classics' of 3...Bg4, back in the days when White
was often taken completely unawares by Black's system. Here the white player,
over 200 points stronger than his opponent, decides to refute Black's opening
by taking all of the offered gifts. I bet you can guess how that turned out...
} 1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 4. f3 Bf5 5. c4 e6 6. dxe6 Nc6 7. Be3 $1 {
Much better.} ({In addition to the suicidal 7 ...exf7+? (as in the previous
game), White often also tries} 7. d5 $2 {However, after} Nb4 8. Na3 fxe6 {
Black is already clearly better. For example} 9. Bd2 exd5 10. Qa4+ Bd7 11. Qb3
Qe7+ $1 12. Kf2 O-O-O 13. Re1 Qc5+ 14. Be3 d4 $1 {and White only lasted a few
more moves in "MickMagpie" (2313) - D. Smerdon, Internet 2014}) 7... Qe7 $1 {
Not as popular as 7...Bb4+, but definitely better. Black's queen takes aim at
White's king along the dangerous, soon-to-be-opened e-file.} 8. exf7+ (8. Nc3
O-O-O $1 {also gives Black a handy initiative. One blitz game I played just a
few weeks before finishing this manuscript continued} 9. Nge2 $2 {, an obvious
developing move, but, as so often in this opening, White can find that the
natural move can easily be a serious mistake.} (9. Qd2 {is a better try, but
Black retains a dangerous initiative after} Nb4 $1 10. O-O-O Qxe6 {; e.g.} 11.
a3 $4 Nc2 12. Bf2 Na1 $1 {, winning}) 9... Nb4 $1 10. Ng3 Nc2+ 11. Kf2 Bg6 12.
Rc1 Nxe3 13. Kxe3 Qxe6+ 14. Kf2 Bc5 $1 15. Nge2 Rhe8 16. Qd2 Ng4+ $3 {(an easy
move to play, even in blitz - the position is just calling out for this
sacrifice)} 17. fxg4 Qf6+ 18. Ke1 Rxd4 $1 19. Nd5 Qh4+ 20. g3 Qxg4 21. Qa5 Rxd5
$1 {and Black soon won in "Jartorio" (2298) - D.Smerdon, Internet 2015.}) 8...
Kxf7 9. Kf2 Re8 10. Qd2 Qd7 $1 {A key move. Black's queen has done an
excellent job, causing far more mischief than the inconvenience caused to her
own kingside. Nevertheless, now is the time to make room for the bishop and
rooks to join the attack. Black is all set to unleash the typical motif ...
Rxe3 and ...Nxd4.} 11. Nc3 ({The novelty} 11. c5 $1 {is best, though} Rxe3 $1
12. Qxe3 Nxd4 13. Bc4+ Be6 $1 {still gives Black a very dangerous attack for
the material.}) 11... Rxe3 $3 {Of course!} 12. Kxe3 Bc5 {Admirable, but not
best.} (12... g6 $1 13. Kf2 Nxd4 {was crushing.}) 13. dxc5 Ng4+ $1 {Every
black move is with tempo, a feature of this opening. White is never given a
moment's rest to develop.} 14. Ke2 (14. fxg4 $4 Re8+ {wins the queen.}) 14...
Qe6+ $2 (14... Qe7+ $1 15. Ne4 (15. Kd1 $4 Ne3+ 16. Kc1 Nxf1 {is winning})
15... Rd8 {forces White to find} 16. Qf4 $1 Nd4+ 17. Ke1 Nc2+ 18. Ke2 {and the
game should end in a draw.}) 15. Kd1 Ne3+ 16. Kc1 {Already White's fifth king
move!} Rd8 (16... Nxf1 $4 17. Nh3 $1 {is why 14 ...Qe7! was preferable.}) 17.
Nd5 Nxf1 18. Qe2 $2 {White buckles under the pressure.} (18. Nh3 $3 {is a
lovely winning shot. But alas, now the white king is in mortal danger.}) 18...
Qh6+ $1 19. f4 Rxd5 $3 {Another cracking sacrifice, ripping away White's last
defensive bastion.} 20. Qxf1 ({Or} 20. cxd5 Qxf4+ 21. Kd1 Ne3+ {and it's all
over.}) 20... Rd4 $1 21. Ne2 Rxc4+ (21... Qe6 $1 {wins on the spot and would
have been a fitting end to a highly energetic performance. Instead, the
ratings of the players begin to show (Black was only 2115) and the game takes
a few entertaining twists and turns, before Black eventually walks away with a
well-earned victory.}) 22. Kd1 Bg4 23. h3 Rd4+ $6 (23... Rxf4 $1 {was still
winning}) 24. Ke1 Bxe2 25. Qxe2 Qg6 26. f5 $2 {White collapses.} ({Black has
let White off the hook somewhat, and now} 26. Kf2 $1 {would have even given
White the better of things.}) 26... Qg3+ 27. Kf1 Rf4+ 28. Kg1 Nd4 $1 29. Qh5+
Kf8 30. Rf1 Rh4 $2 (30... Re4 $1 {and} 31. -- Ne2+ {wins quickly.}) 31. Qd1 Re4
32. Rf2 Re1+ 33. Qxe1 Nf3+ 34. Kf1 $4 (34. Rxf3 $1 {is unclear, after all of
that!}) 34... Nxe1 35. Kxe1 Qe3+ 36. Re2 Qc1+ {A fitting final result to an
inspiring performance by Black, despite a rollercoaster of mutual errors along
the way.} 0-1

