{Sergei Krivoshey is not a name many chess players are familiar with, although
the Ukrainian GM has amassed an impressive array of scalps with his unorthodox
play. Perhaps no other grandmaster has contributed as much to the theory of
our opening over the past fifteen years. This game, one of Krivoshey's early
efforts, neatly encompasses his uncompromisingly entertaining style.} 1. e4 d5
2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 4. f3 Bf5 5. Bb5+ Nbd7 6. c4 e6 7. dxe6 Bxe6 8. d5 Bf5 9.
Nc3 Bc5 {A very popular and high-scoring move. Black's bishop immediately
targets White's weakened kingside dark squares.} 10. Qe2+ {The only move to
try for an advantage.} (10. Nge2 $2 O-O {is just horrible for White.}) 10...
Qe7 (10... Kf8 $5 {is interesting, although Black shouldn't really be afraid
of the queen exchange as her activity remains immense. After} 11. Be3 $1 Qe7 (
11... Kg8 $5 {is an interesting new idea; see the theory}) 12. Bxd7 (12. Bf4 a6
{is fine for Black}) 12... Nxd7 13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Qf2 $1 Qxc4 15. Nge2 Qc5 $1 {
, White has a slight, but manageable edge.}) 11. g4 $5 (11. Qxe7+ Kxe7 {is
more common; for example,} 12. Bf4 a6 $1 13. Ba4 Nb6 $1 14. Bb3 Bd3 $1 15. Bxc7
Rac8 $1 16. Bxb6 Bxb6 {with excellent compensation for the pawns.}) 11... Bg6 (
11... Bd3 {(as in O.Renet-L.Galego, European Club Cup, Eupen 1994) is more to
the point, and if} 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. Bf4 {then} a6 $1 {with sufficient
compensation.}) 12. Bg5 O-O-O 13. Qxe7 Bxe7 14. Bxd7+ {Otherwise ...Nc5 may be
embarrassing for the b5-bishop.} Rxd7 {A typical sort of endgame for the 9...
Bc5 variation. Black has secured the two bishops and has excellent open lines
for the pieces to enjoy. Meanwhile, White's centre is far weaker than it
appears, with c4 being a particularly tender spot. The shot ...h7-h5 is in the
air, while Black's knight can also find activity on the queenside via d7-c5/e5.
Black's compensation is undoubtedly enough for the pawn.} 15. O-O-O Re8 (15...
h5 $1 {immediately was strong.}) 16. Nh3 h5 $1 17. Rhg1 hxg4 18. fxg4 Bc5 $1 {
The bishop pair cut through the board like two dark lasers, while the open
e-file is for Black's rooks alone to enjoy.} 19. Rge1 Rde7 20. Rxe7 Rxe7 21.
Ng1 $2 ({The shamefully passive} 21. Rh1 {was best, after which White can put
up stubborn resistance.}) 21... Re5 $1 22. Bf4 ({Or} 22. Bxf6 Be3+ $1) 22...
Nxg4 $1 23. b4 Rf5 $1 {Without even a pawn to compensate for the positional
defects, White is busted.} 24. Nge2 Rxf4 $1 25. Nxf4 Be3+ 26. Kb2 Bxf4 27. Rd4
Ne5 $1 28. Kb3 Bxh2 {Black has an overwhelming material advantage, to which
White quickly succumbs.} 29. Rh4 Nf3 30. Rh8+ Kd7 31. Na4 b6 0-1

