1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 4. f3 Bf5 5. g4 $1 {If there is an absolute
refutation of 3 d4 Bg4, it must be this. White's outlandish approach has been
rarely seen in over-the-board practice; in fact, I have never faced this
variation in literally hundreds of games in this opening, and it is simply
omitted in most published texts on 3...Bg4. However, this system has been
successfully employed within the correspondence community, which speaks to its
merit. The variation's development was also furthered by FM Michiel Wind in
2008, who championed the white cause in the German chess magazine Kaissiber.
(My thanks go to the editor, Stefan B√ºcker, for providing me with a copy of
the magazine and also for useful comments.) --- Wind's analysis, coupled with
robust testing in subsequent correspondence games and my own extensive
analysis, has led me to conclude that this is by far the most serious threat
to the viability of the Portuguese complex. In fact, if computers ever manage
to solve the game of chess, I have a feeling that this line may well be
recorded as the ultimate refutation of 3...Bg4. --- Okay, I've painted a
rather bleak picture of Black's chances in that brutally honest introduction.
But before you ask your bookstore for a refund, let's look at the flipside of
the equation. First of all, like so many computer-inspired variations, the
strength of White's approach comes from precise, concrete lines, many of which
defy human logic. White's early g2-g4 thrust means that she is unlikely to be
able to castle safely, not just in the near future, but most probably not at
all. Additionally, at several branches of the analysis White will be forced to
neglect her development further in order to justify her greed; in some cases,
White's first ten or more moves will all be pawn moves - and this will be
absolutely necessary in order for her to stay in the game! --- My point is
that White's extreme disregard for classical opening principles in the name of
grabbing material leaves her position hanging by a thread - although, with
best play, it does indeed appear to hold on. Black has several, attractive,
dangerous options at different moves, and while White's position seems to be
robust against each with best play, there are simply too many lines for a
human to memorize. Inaccuracies by Black lead to positions where she has
insufficient, but tricky, compensation. Inaccuracies by White are often fatal.
--- Keep this in mind as you go through the chapter. Remembering the
infrequency of this variation in tournament play, I would recommend not
spending too much time committing the analysis to memory; instead, it is more
important to simply be aware that the variation exists, and to familiarize
yourself with Black's common ideas. --- I don't want this to read as a
dismissal or an excuse; in correspondence chess, for example, I believe that
White's chances of winning with this variation are high, which is reflected by
its popularity in this genre. However, in an over-the-board human contest,
White has to overcome almost insurmountable practical difficulties in order to
keep her position together. Even if your opponent has spent several hours
delving into deep computer analysis, I can't imagine her being able to
memorize all of the variations necessary to nurse a theoretical advantage to
fruition - Black simply has too many possibilities that give her excellent
play and the typical 'almost-sufficient compensation'. --- From a practical
perspective, if I ever do face 5 g4, I am confident of being able to bamboozle
an opponent over the board in the crazy, razor-sharp tactics that emerge, in
which White really needs to walk on a knife's edge in order to keep an
advantage. On the other hand, Black's position sure is a lot more fun!} Bg6 (
5... Bd7 $5 {is covered in the theory and leads to less explored positions,
though objectively White can keep a sound advantage with precise play.}) 6. c4
$1 {In the few encounters featuring this variation, Black has usually
continued with 6...e6 and we will take this as the main line; however, the
rarely played 6...c6!? comes into consideration too (this option is in fact so
rare that one of our illustrative games is an all-engine match I ran on my
home computer!). Nevertheless, despite its infrequency in practice, the
Correspondence deserves our attention and careful study. Understand these
positions and you can feel confident that you will be better able to navigate
the murky waters than your opponents.} *

