six pawn moves in a row, and might well add a seventh. While this may seem
extraordinarily cheeky, White isn't that far behind in development; after all,
Black has moved her bishop three times already, and her f6-knight is about to
be kicked offside. --- From our perspective, White will usually try to blow us
off the board over the next few moves, fighting us with our own style as she
seemingly ignores positional considerations in favour of concrete tactics. The
knight on c3, combined with the coming g4-g5 thrust, ensures that she will
keep control over d5. The queen usually lines up against our king from e2,
while her own king can tuck in at f2 if necessarily. A kingside pawn storm is
often on the cards, while the kingside minor pieces usually swing in to the
game via the h3-square. All up, White's position contains a lot of hidden
attacking potential. --- If all of that has managed to scare you, well, that
was the intention! You should definitely not take White's set-up for granted.
But never fear; there is plenty of good news for the black side as well. For
the moment, at least, White hasn't got a single piece out from its starting
position, whereas Black is just two moves from castling. This is actually the
key trump in our hand: while the white king will have a hard time finding
long-term security, Black's will (usually) be safely tucked away for when the
fireworks start. --- While the main lines analysed by the correspondence
community have usually focused on Black's attempts to win back her pawn,
naturally, we will prefer to forego the material and play for maximum activity.
The only way to combat White's attempt at an outright refutation is to stand
up to the challenge and fight fire with fire. --- From the diagram, White has
a choice of move-orders, which will likely to lead to the same thing if Black
quickly takes on d5. However, Black has several good reasons to avoid this,
not least because White can often use an open e-file to her advantage. The
pawn on e6 is actually doing a good job at the moment, both blocking the
e-file from an annoying Qe2+ and controlling the f5-square against a quick
f4-f5 assault. Black may well break the tension on d5 at some point, but for
the moment, she should prefer to develop her king's bishop and quickly castle,
exploiting her lead in development to maximum effect. A key theme is meeting
Qb3 with the odd-looking counter ...c7-c5. In fact, even without provocation,
Black can often attack White's central pawn phalanx with this move to open up
some squares and lines for the black minor pieces. --- White's best move by
far is 7 Nc3, but first we will examine the alternatives. If you're looking
for quick memory-markers, my advice is: after 7 g5 Nfd7 8 Nc3, play 8...Be7!;
if White goes for 7 Nc3, play 7...c5! so as to answer 8 g5 with 8...cxd4!.} 7.
