{"Wuss, n. A person regarded as weak, ineffectual, or overly fearful."} 1. e4
d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 4. Be2 {Wimpy, but logical. This is the most common
response to 3...Bg4, particularly at club levels. By exchanging off
light-squared bishops, White seeks to suppress Black's attacking potential as
well as hasten her own kingside development. --- Black, for her part, does not
have to be compliant. Natural development and kingside castling is sound and
good enough for equality, but unless White is accurate, Black can instead opt
to castle queenside. With the kings housed on opposite wings, an attacking
race ensues in which Black's main battering ram is her g-pawn. A typical
combative set-up involves playing (after ...Bxe2) ...Qxd5, ...Nc6, ...e7-e6, ..
.0-0-0, ...Bd6, ...Rhg8 and ...g7-g5-g4 etc. Despite White's fourth move being
designed to tame the position, I am happy to report that Black's aggressive
intentions cannot be underestimated! --- Although this variation is not
critical and immediately guarantees Black equal chances, the frequency with
which you will encounter it demands that we pay it close attention. Become
familiar with the themes and ideas of the Wuss, and you will be rewarded with
easy games and cheap points.} *

