1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 4. Bb5+ Nbd7 5. Be2 $1 {This relatively rare
retreat is an anti-Portuguese system that deserves your close attention. The
clever switchback by the bishop, taking advantage of Black's hemmed-in queen,
dampens Black's short-term attacking chances. --- The attraction of 5 Be2 lies
in its simplicity: White heads for a small but stable advantage by immediately
returning the pawn, while significantly reducing Black's counterplay. While
this could never be deemed an outright refutation, it is certainly a powerful
practical choice for White, who more often than not is looking for a simple,
theory-free panacea to our weapon. --- At first, it might seem like White has
just wasted a tempo compared to the Wuss (4 Be2). However, things are not so
simple. In those variations Black recaptures the pawn on d5 with her queen,
which usually finds an active post on f5 or h5. Her knight will jump to c6,
where it will pressure d4, support ...e7-e5 and facilitate queenside castling.
--- By tempting the black knight to d7 first, White circumvents this natural
development. Black must now recapture on d5 with her king's knight, which will
invariably be forced to retreat back to f6 in any case. Moreover, the traffic
jam on the d-file will mean that Black has to evacuate the king to the
kingside and try to arrange her pieces in a somewhat cramped fashion on the
first three ranks. In fact, compared to 4 Be2, Black often finds herself
lacking in both space and time. --- Once again, I must confess that I have
tried to scare you into taking careful notice of this chapter. So, now to the
good news. As you might have already guessed, the resulting positions are
incredibly underexplored. With the exception of this book, there is
practically no theory on this variation, which is excellent news for two
important reasons: 1. You will be much better prepared to tackle the
subtleties of the game; and 2. White has to play extremely accurately to cause
us any problems. --- Furthermore, without compromising on quality, I have
chosen to focus our repertoire on lines involving pawn sacrifices, material
imbalances and complex, unorthodox structures. I have done this in order to
maximize the practical advantages of our familiarity with the variation, and
to give our opponents every opportunity to err. --- The bottom line is: Don't
feel disheartened if you see 5 Be2 on your board. With solid preparation and a
sensible approach, you should see your practical results flourish. We are
playing for fun and for fire, to balance risk and return. After all, that's
our philosophy, remember?} *

