1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 Bg4 4. Bb5+ c6 $5 {In an episode from the third
season of the fantastic television series The West Wing, Leo McGarry, the
Chief of Staff to the President of the United States, talks about the concept
of "throwing an elbow". He tells a story about legendary basketball centre
Bill Russell of the Boston Celtics. Russell was struggling against his
opposite numbers because he chose to play by the rules rather than 'play
dirty'. As Leo tells it: "Russell was getting eaten alive because they could
never get him to throw an elbow. He didn't want to do it. So, Coach Red
Auerbach told him to do it one time. 'Throw an elbow in a nationally televised
game. You'll never have to do it again.'" --- As much as I could go on and on
about The West Wing, there is a point. As I mentioned earlier, 4 Bb5+ Nbd7 5
Be2 is an incredibly rare variation, but that doesn't mean it won't grow in
popularity in the future - particularly because it could be seen as a nice,
safe, 'easy' way to get a small plus. And indeed, as we saw, White never faces
too many dangers and certainly doesn't have to learn much theory to stay out
of trouble in the main lines. --- Recently, the inventive Australian IM Guy
West, one of the country's first regular Scandinavian players, complained to
me that a few guys in his local club had started playing this variation
against him regularly, much to his annoyance. But he didn't want to resort to
4...c6 because he thought it was fundamentally unsound - which is possibly
true. --- I wrote back and told him to "throw an elbow". As we saw, Black has
good chances of equalizing against 4...Nbd7 5 Be2, but it's a tough line to
drum up winning chances. However, 4...c6!? leads to far more complicated
positions where Black's pieces quickly reach active posts, and against which
White must play accurately not only to keep an advantage, but even to stay out
of trouble. There's theory to learn, and the positions aren't going to suit
players looking for a calmer game. And even if White manages to navigate the
murky opening swamp, the resulting endgames seem to give Black just enough
compensation to take half a point - at least, my engines consistently make
draws in the many simulations I've run. --- The point is that an opponent is
far less likely to play 4 Bb5+ if she knows she has to learn the theory on yet
another crazy sacrifice after 4...c6!? - that is, if you've developed a
reputation by "throwing an elbow" in this line before. Not only is it a great
surprise weapon - Black scores 60% with it in over-the-board play, and even
higher in blitz - it is likely going to be off-putting for future opponents.
--- So even if you don't believe in the soundness of what follows, I suggest
you add it to the memory bank, and throw it out there once in a while. It
might pay dividends not only as a surprise weapon, but also as a useful
deterrent!} 5. dxc6 Nxc6 {At first, it is hard to believe Black can drum up
sufficient attacking chances against the white position. But Black's
compensation manifests itself a little more subtly in this variation. She
usually obtains the bishop pair after White plays Bxc6 (and sometimes even
Bg5xf6), and can seek to exploit this by eventually opening up the game
through ...e7/e6-e5 or ...c6-c5 breaks. --- Meanwhile, White often finds it
difficult to coordinate her pieces due to pressure on the d4-, c2-and b2-pawns.
The pin on the f3-knight can also be very annoying, and attempts to break it
with h2-h3 and g2-g4 often lead to disaster after Black sacrifices with ...
Nxg4. While there are no obvious attacking motifs, Black often enjoys full or
almost-full compensation, active pieces, and easy play.} *

