1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. d4 {This is a very popular line in practice, as it can
occur both from the stated move-order,} ({and via} 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. d4) 3... Bg4
4. Nf3 Qxd5 {It is often employed by opponents who, when surprised by 3...Bg4,
take the attitude, "Surely simple development can't be wrong." On the contrary,
Black can quickly whip up dangerous pressure on the d4-pawn with ...Nc6, ...
0-0-0 and ...e7-e5 (usually after swinging the queen to the kingside). ---
Given that the kings will be castled on opposite wings, it should come as no
surprise that Black can plan a rapid attack against the white monarch. When
the black queen is eventually persuaded to relocate (after Nc3 or c2-c4, or
even voluntarily), she often chooses between h5 and f5. Clearly h5 is the more
aggressive post, but it should be noted that Black is then committed to
answering h2-h3 with a piece sacrifice by playing a quick ...e7-e5!. Such
sacrifices don't tend to work with the queen on f5; from here, Black can
answer h2-h3 with ...Bxf3 and usually ...e7-e5 anyway. As a general rule of
thumb, f5 is your default square after c2-c4 or if you need to move it
voluntarily, while Nc3 can usually be answered by ...Qh5. Another way of
looking at it is that f5 is generally always a safe choice for your queen,
even after Nc3. --- I have an excellent score in the Classical, perhaps the
highest out of all variations in our system. In my experience, the Wuss and
the Classical are the two anti-Portuguese variations in which you will
encounter the greatest number of opponents who don't know the theory and are
simply looking for a safe way to escape the opening. In the Classical, however,
this is a very dubious strategy. Rather than a safe choice, this variation
demands precision and theoretical preparedness from White in order to stay
afloat. Become familiar with the traps and tricks in the lines that follow,
and you will be able to score yourself many, many easy points. --- It should
be noted that the Classical variation often transposes to either the 2...Qxd5
Scandinavian or the Nimzowitsch Defence (1 e4 Nc6), although there are some
differences in our system as Black has already committed to ...Nf6. This means
there is a small percentage of players who are familiar with the white side of
things from other systems, and therefore may be well versed in the intricacies
of the Classical. I faced such an opponent in our first illustrative game. My
point is that you shouldn't automatically assume that you are facing a
theoretically naive opponent just because they play in this fashion, even if
the chances of this at club levels are statistically high. --- What follows
may seem like a mass of cross-references and variations, but don't worry: the
actual material required by Black to master this line is quite moderate. Many
of the variations transpose, depending on White's chosen move-order, and
rarely does the exact sequence affect Black's standard plan of ...Nc6, ...
0-0-0, ...Qh5/f5 and ...e7-e5. I have tried to be as thorough as possible with
detailing all likely move-orders, but this is more for your personal reference
than a request to memorize each line. --- But before we wade into the jungle,
let's again ease ourselves in by looking at some model games.} *

