1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. c4 {The principled 3 c4 was once a reasonably popular
means of meeting the 2...Nf6 Scandinavian, particularly as it was thought to
force a transposition to the formerly-fashionable Panov-Botvinnik Attack of
the Caro-Kann Defence after 3...c6 4 d4. The decline in popularity of 3 c4 is
due to two important theoretical developments. Firstly, the Panov-Botvinnik
Attack is no longer considered one of White's critical attempts at an
advantage against the Caro-Kann, with Black having done a good job at refining
her defensive strategies over the past few decades. Secondly, and no less
importantly, the discovery of the so-called Icelandic Gambit, which is
introduced by 3...e6, put many white players off the trail. This gambit (which
should more appropriately be named the Palme Gambit, after its inventor, the
Austrian master Rudolf Palme) gives Black splendid activity and very real
chances of scoring quick victories in tournament play. --- In modern times, it
seems that 3 c4 is seen as only inviting Black to make a pleasant choice
between adopting a rock-solid transposition to an acceptable variation of the
Caro-Kann, or unleashing a venomous gambit. Gradually, 3 c4 has slipped down
the list of White's frequent third-move alternatives, now sitting behind 3 Nf3,
3 Bb5+ and even 3 Nc3, as well as the still hugely popular main line 3 d4.
Despite that, there are good reasons to take 3 c4 seriously. Stylistically,
the main lines of the Panov-Botvinnik Attack generally require Black to defend
quite passively, usually playing prosaically against a white isolated queen's
pawn. On the other hand, the 'accepted' main line of the Icelandic Gambit
clearly seems to favour White after accurate play. Bearing this in mind,
practically speaking, a player comfortable with the transposition to the
Panov-Botvinnik would be advised to consider adopting 3 c4 as their first
choice. --- Nevertheless, the message in these chapters is quite positive from
Black's perspective. First, an important improvement in the main line of the
Icelandic Gambit (7...Bf5!) resurrects this exciting variation. Secondly,
Black has the option (after 3...c6) to wield a dangerous sideline in the
Panov-Botvinnik that comes complete with surprise value, pawn sacrifices and
quick, daring attacks against the white king. I have included my analysis on
both options (3...e6 and 3...c6) so that you can pick and choose your poison
according to your tastes and the demands of each situation.} *

