1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. c4 c6 {As opposed to 3...e6, accepting the gambit
after 3...c6 is not considered White's best option. There are two reasons for
this. The first is because Black is effectively one move faster with her
development after 4 dxc6 Nxc6, as her light-squared bishop will reach an
active location on f5 or g4 in one move rather than (after 3...e6 4 dxe6 Bxe6)
in two. The second reason is that, after 3...c6 4 dxc6, Black can follow up
with a quick ...e7-e5, immediately controlling or challenging the centre.  On
the other hand, declining the gambit with 3...c6 4 d4 now makes a lot more
sense. The transposition to the Caro-Kann's Panov-Botvinnik Attack typically
leads to positions where White has an isolated queen's pawn, strikingly
similar to those often reached from a Nimzo-Indian Defence or even a Queen's
Gambit Accepted. These lines are sound and perfectly acceptable for Black from
a theoretical perspective, but they lack a certain panache for players whose
heart is set on the sort of excitement we've seen after 3 d4 Bg4. Therefore,
we will investigate an interesting sideline of the Panov-Botvinnik that is
more, shall we say, 'stylistically appropriate'.} *

