1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. Nf3 {For many players on the black side, this is
considered the most annoying move to face for our repertoire. It has been
believed in some circles for quite some time now that this move should
essentially circumvent any Portuguese-style ...Bg4 gambits. Of course, this is
a matter of opinion... However, before we have a look at the different
variations, it is worthwhile discussing why 3 Nf3 is considered such a pain.
First, note that after...} Qxd5 4. Nc3 {Black's queen doesn't have a good
square to run to.} (4. Nc3 Qa5 {will transpose to an orthodox Scandinavian (2..
.Qxd5),} ({while} 4... Qf5 {blocks our own bishop from the g4-square.})) 4...
Qh5 $6 {The seemingly consistent choice.} 5. Be2 Bg4 6. O-O Nc6 {...only leads
to problems for Black after...} 7. h3 $1 Bxf3 ({Unfortunately,} 7... O-O-O $2 {
just doesn't work if White hasn't played d2-d4. After} 8. hxg4 Nxg4 9. d3 ({or
} 9. Ne4 $1) 9... e5 10. Ne4 Nd4 11. Re1 {, Black's attack is already flailing,
M.Godena-R.Damaso, Lisbon Zonal 1993.}) ({The consistent} 7... Bxh3 $2 8. gxh3
Qxh3 {also leads nowhere after} 9. Ng5 $1 {; for example,} Qh4 10. d3 h6 11.
Nge4 {and White is winning, A.Yagubi-I.Brikov, Tula 2014.}) 8. Bxf3 Qf5 ({Or}
8... Qc5 9. d3 e6 10. Be3 {with a clear advantage to White, A.Kosteniuk-A.
Muzychuk, Beijing (blitz) 2013.}) 9. d4 {Black is left in a passive position,
underdeveloped and with little chance of counterplay, F.Nijboer-P.Vandevoort,
Brussels Zonal 1993. --- This raises an important point worth mentioning about
3 Nf3. It is seen nowhere near as often as the main move 3 d4, largely because
it allows Black a reasonably favourable transposition to the 'normal'
Scandinavian after 3...Qxd5 4 Nc3 Qa5, while cutting out popular sidelines
that either delay Nf3 or omit it all together. (The same cannot be said if
Black chooses to transpose to other Scandinavian variations via 4...Qd6 or 3...
Nxd5, in which White invariably plays an early Nf3.) Several strong players
have chosen to add a second Scandinavian system to their overall black
repertoire for this very reason. --- On the other hand, I personally believe
that the lines I have presented below are perfectly acceptable for Black, and
so we now move to the main dish of this section: 3...Bg4. --- I have named the
(previously unnamed) subvariations with a particular culinary flair. My
apologies in advance for this, but a chess author has to have a bit of fun
every now and then. There are three key differences that White can try to
exploit after the consistent 3...Bg4. --- To begin with, White can utilize the
extra tempo from delaying d2-d4 by playing 4 c4, followed by a quick Qb3,
protecting d5 and targeting b7. Essentially, she is attempting to transpose
into positions similar to sharp lines of the Panov-Botvinnik Caro-Kann, having
arguably saved a tempo by delaying d2-d4. This approach is quite rare in
practice but was the recipe recommended by some friends of mine, who are noted
Hungarian theoreticians. I've cooked up our own secret antidote to their
'Goulash'. --- Second, note that White's third move puts her one move closer
to castling kingside (as compared with 3 d4). Thus, she can try to play in
classical fashion via 4 Be2 and a quick 0-0 and h2-h3 before Black has had
time to organize the standard counterplay using the d4- and e5-squares. In
such positions, Black rarely wants to retreat her bishop to h5, where it
deprives the black queen of an important square, and so an early exchange on
f3 is likely to be necessary. I then propose that we play ...Nc6, allowing an
ugly doubling of our c-pawns. Ugly doesn't necessarily mean unwholesome,
however, and I have full confidence that you will find my beloved 'Celeriac'
very good for your health. --- Finally, and most importantly, White can follow
up 3 Nf3 Bg4 with 4 Bb5+. Here, the Elbow-like 4...c6?! fails to deliver
sufficient compensation, while after the natural 4...Nbd7, White has the
powerful intermezzo 5 h3!. This line is rarely played in practice, but it has
been suggested in a couple of published books in recent years as a simple
recipe to gain an easy advantage against our opening - the perfect choice for
many players, such as my friend Charlie. I imagine that this variation's
popularity will increase in the future. In fact 5 h3 presents one of the
biggest challenges to our repertoire, but we will see that with careful play
and the help of some home-cooked analysis, Black can secure decent chances.
--- But first of all, a couple of quick appetizers to give this section some
flavour.} *

