1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. Nf3 Bg4 {The day before, I had secured my third and
final Grandmaster norm, irrespective of the result of this game. With the
pressure off, it was time to have some fun, and so it is no surprise that 3...
Bg4 appeared on the board. Plus, I had a new idea I was aching to try out...}
4. Be2 Qxd5 5. Nc3 Qf5 $1 6. h3 {One of the key points of delaying d2-d4.
White immediately seeks to break the pin on f3, and in so doing hopes to
complete the development phase before Black can build up pressure in the
centre via ...Nc6 and ...0-0-0. However...} Bxf3 7. Bxf3 Nc6 $1 {A new idea.
It takes a certain aesthetic blindness to come up with such an ugly move, as
my colleagues were quick to remind me after the game. However, to quote
Christina Aguilera, 'You are beautiful, no matter what they say.' (Yes, I have
rather eclectic music tastes.)} 8. Bxc6+ bxc6 {Chess is so simple: You put
your king on d7 (but of course), a bishop on d6, a rook on g8, and then just
push your g-pawn down the board and deliver mate. Easy. --- Okay, I jest - if
only a little. There was a time when the masters would laugh at such a crude
structure, but the days of isolated, doubled pawns being considered a fatal
weakness are long gone. In modern chess, dynamic considerations and concrete
variations often outweigh the Nimzowitschian evaluation of positional elements.
This is one such case. --- Despite my postmodern standpoint on chess analysis,
it is still possible to explain my faith in Black's position in more familiar,
classical terms. For starters, the black king will be surprisingly safe on d7,
where the doubled c-pawns will actually provide a handy barrier against
unwelcome invasions. Combined with a pawn on e6, bishop on d6, and knight on
the excellent semi-outpost on d5, the black king can hardly be called exposed.
Moreover, all of Black's pieces will soon become more active than their
counterparts; the rooks will have important roles to play along the semi-open
b-file and (soon to be) semi-open g-file. This puts the white king in quite a
predicament, because it is clear that, whichever side of the board he chooses
to hide, an attack is imminent. --- I have scored 100% from the diagram in
several encounters since this game (usually in blitz, to be fair), and
experience has taught me that White's position is by no means easy to defend.
Black's attacking plan is straightforward and surprisingly fast. Moreover,
there's something deliciously cheeky about the entire set-up that I must
confess gives me an extra kick, especially after the inevitable ...Kd7!.} 9.
Qe2 ({For} 9. d3 e6 10. O-O Bd6 11. Qe2 g5 $5 {- see the theory section.}) 9...
e6 ({Not} 9... Qxc2 $6 10. Qc4 $1 {is annoying.}) 10. O-O Bd6 ({After} 10...
Qxc2 $6 11. Qc4 {, Black can now defend the pawn with} Kd7 {, but White has
more than sufficient compensation along the c-file. If we are going to flaunt
the rules by putting the king on d7, we should at least stick to the program!})
11. Qc4 Kd7 $5 {As the saying goes, "Weak pawns are only weak if they can be
attacked." Here, Black's pawns are easily defended. Black's position is
actually quite healthy: all of her pieces are superior to their opposite
numbers, and Black's king is no less secure than White's monarch. Normal moves
in the middlegame are ...Rb8, ...g7-g5 (often prepared by ...Rg8) and ...Nd5,
from where the knight can jump to f4. White has to act quickly.} ({
Interestingly, Black's lead in development is so impressive that she could
even sacrifice the c6-pawn. In fact, despite my fond attachment to 11...Kd7,
