1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. Nf3 Bg4 4. c4 $5 {This move was a proposed refutation
by the esteemed Hungarian trainer IM Laszlo Hazai. A week after I trained with
him in Budapest, his student, GM Krisztian Szabo, played this variation
against me at a tournament in a small town in central Hungary. The tournament
was a disaster for me, but the company and the culture made up for it, and the
goulash was out of this world. Given that I dropped thirty points in the event,
it's little wonder the food is the main memory I've chosen to keep... ---
Krisztian achieved a slight advantage in our game and I was forced to dig deep
to earn half a point, but we shall see that Black has a powerful and exciting
improvement.} e6 5. dxe6 ({Here,} 5. dxe6 Nc6 6. Be2 fxe6 {was the routine
continuation of Kr.Szabo-D.Smerdon, Paks 2007, but Black can improve with the
surprising novelty:}) 5... Bxf3 $3 6. Qxf3 Nc6 $3 {This is much more in the
spirit of our opening! The voluntary exchange on f3 is unique to our system,
but here it has a very concrete point: Black now has a fantastic outpost on
the d4-square, while White's queen will find herself cut off from retreat if
she plays Be2, after which her majesty will be relentlessly hunted around the
board. --- This line is still untested in tournament play, but I have had the
chance to try it out many times in blitz and rapid chess. From both these
games and my own analysis, I have concluded that Black has dangerous and fully
sufficient compensation for the material.} 7. exf7+ {White will most likely
have to make this move sooner or later.} ({Otherwise:} 7. d3 Nd4 8. Qd1 Qe7 $1
{gives Black an excellent position.}) (7. Nc3 Nd4 8. Qd1 {was tried against me
in a blitz game, which continued} Bc5 ({again} 8... Qe7 $1 {is stronger.} 9.
Be2 Qxe6 10. O-O O-O-O {with full compensation}) 9. d3 O-O 10. Be3 Re8 $2 (
10... Nxe6 $1 {was correct}) 11. exf7+ {(The right moment)} Kxf7 12. a3 $4 (12.
Be2 $1 {would have left Black struggling to justify her sacrifices}) 12... Nf5
$1 {and Black is winning, Linkmus (2450)-D.Smerdon, Internet 2012.}) 7... Kxf7
{Black is two pawns down, but her pieces are about to spring to life, while
White's only developed piece - her foolhardy queen - will soon find herself a
target for Black's pieces. In particular, the d4 outpost and the recklessly
open e-file are just begging to be exploited by the black forces. Despite her
material advantage, White's position is already precarious, and one false step
over the next few moves could easily spell an immediate downfall. Even with
best play, White can hope for equality at most.} 8. -- {White has three
acceptable continuations, of which the best is not at all obvious:} (8. Be2 {
(see variation A1)}) (8. Qd1 {(see variation A2)}) (8. c5 $1 {(see variation
A3)}) ({Other moves are clearly worse. --- The attempt to return some of the
material by} 8. Nc3 $6 Bc5 $1 {is obviously bad, with ...Re8 and ...Nd4
arriving quickly.}) (8. d3 $6 Bb4+ 9. Bd2 $2 Re8+ {also gave Black a winning
position in Gigi111 (2200)-D.Smerdon, Internet 2014.}) (8. d4 $2 {(attempting
to return some of the material)} Nxd4 9. Qd3 Bb4+ 10. Nc3 {as in jncool68
(2534)-D.Smerdon, Internet 2012, backfires, as} Qe7+ 11. Be3 Rhd8 $1 {is
completely winning for Black.}) *

