solid and safe, while requiring little preparation. When he asked me for the
best no-nonsense approach against my own opening, I didn't hesitate in
recommending 5 h3. Charlie was happy. --- This innocent-looking move is in
fact a serious attempt at a refutation. This is an inconvenient moment for
Black to have to decide what to do with her bishop on g4. In general, as you
should know by now, Black primarily answers h2-h3 with ...Bxf3, followed
immediately by capturing on d5. However, here White can take advantage of the
omission of d2-d4 to secure the d5-pawn, leaving Black bereft of counterplay.
On the other hand, retreating the bishop to h5 will leave Black's queen
exposed when she eventually lands on d5, as her usual h5- and f5-squares are
no longer realistically available. The consequence of this quandary is that
White can aim for positions that are comfortable, simple and relatively safe -
a perfect choice for Charlie. --- The position after 5 h3 is, from the
perspective of our repertoire, quite rare. Nonetheless, I consider it to be
one of White's best ways of responding to 3...Bg4. Furthermore, it has been
recommended by some highly-regarded chess authors, such as GM John Emms, GM
Larry Kaufman and IM Andrew Greet, so Black should definitely be prepared to
handle this variation. These authors give Black's position a very negative
prognosis, but I will argue that things are not as bad as they seem; in fact,
equipped with a good understanding of this variation, Black should be able to
hold her own, even if the lines aren't as fun as those in other parts of this
book. --- I consider 5...Bh5! to be Black's best option, but it is worth
looking at the alternatives to see why Black's position is so fragile after
other moves. Also, you may decide that you don't like the slightly more
passive nature of the positions after 5...Bh5 and would prefer to roll the
dice with a riskier variation. Consequently, we will also take a closer look
at 5...a6!?. While being objectively inferior, this move does offer more
active possibilities and forces White to play accurately in order to secure an
advantage.} (5... a6 $5 {(see variation C1)}) (5... Bh5 $1 {(see variation C2)}
