1. e4 d5 2. exd5 Nf6 3. Bb5+ {This is equally White's second-most played
option (joint with 3 c4), and has been regularly employed by many strong
players, but I have never understood its popularity. There is some basic logic
to developing the bishop outside of the pawn chain before defending d5 with
c2-c4. However, after 3...Nbd7, Black will usually be able to exchange off
this bishop for her knight in a couple of moves, when her own light-squared
bishop can turn into a monster. After the standard undermining procedure of ...
a7-a6 and ...b7-b5, Black's bishop can find excellent work from either b7 or
a6, while White will often be saddled with one or two isolated d-pawns. Black
can also opt to break down the pawn centre with ...c7-c6 or ...e7-e6 as the
situation dictates; in every scenario, the bishop pair and superior structure
guarantee Black excellent compensation, and often much more than that. --- As
you can see, I have great faith in Black's chances after 3...Nbd7, which is
the most natural choice to me, although it isn't actually the main line.} Nbd7
({Instead,} 3... Bd7 {is more popular, after which White scores quite well
with the tame retreat} 4. Be2 {, though even here I have faith that Black's
potential can be maximized with the extremely rare gambit} c6 $5 {. I have
done a lot of my own analysis on this line and have found some very
interesting new ideas for Black - so much so that I have decided to cover 3...
Bd7 as well. However, note that my main recommendation for Black remains 3...
Nbd7, and this move will form the basis for the following illustrative games.})
