1. e4 d5 {Every now and then you will face an opponent who, either through
shock, fear or just sheer spite, will refuse to engage in the tactical anarchy
that comprises the previous four sections. In the final part of the book, we
will briefly consider White's lesser alternatives that, nonetheless, rear
their ugly heads on occasion. --- In short, while nothing in this chapter is
theoretically scary, it is worth spending the time to learn the appropriate
remedies to these lesser alternatives. Doing so will help you transform your
opening positions from easy equality into targeted advantages, and help you
turn those half points into full ones.} 2. -- ({Despite being completely
harmless,} 2. exd5 Nf6 3. Nc3 {appears quite often in practice. In fact, it
has historically been played more frequently than 3 Nf3, which, as we saw, is
a serious attempt at an advantage. The same cannot be said for the queen's
knight's move, but because you will almost certainly face this variation with
some regularity, I have covered it in far more detail than typically accorded
by previous authors of the Scandinavian. Spend the time to understand this
system; it is definitely a worthy investment.}) ({The other variations covered
in this section are far less common.} 2. Nc3 {is simply a bad move in my
opinion, although it is hard to believe that White can actually be worse.
Black should take the chance to grab space and the initiative with} d4 {after
which she has excellent chances to claim an advantage.}) (2. d4 $6 {initiates
the Blackmar-Diemer Gambit, which retains a small but devoted following at
club levels. In a sense, countering Black's sacrifice with a gambit of her own
is an interesting psychological ploy by White. And in fact, you can easily get
in trouble as Black with natural moves if you don't know what you're doing.
You may only face this variation roughly one time in a hundred, but your
opponent likely plays it exclusively and will thus be much better versed in
its subtleties. For this reason, I have again chosen to devote more space to
the BDG than has commonly been considered by other authors. However, there's
no reason to fear. The gambit really is unsound, and with just a little bit of
memorization you can guarantee yourself a hefty opening advantage whenever you
find yourself facing the BDG.}) ({We'll finish things off with a short look at
} 2. e5 $6 {Like its cousin 2 Nc3, this move allows Black to transpose to an
improved version of a French or Caro-Kann, should you wish it. However, once
again I am going to recommend playing for the maximum. With just a couple of
accurate moves, Black can emerge from the opening with at least a slight
advantage.}) *

