9. -- {We have reached the key tabiya for 3 Nc3, and you will certainly see
this position many times in your Scandinavian career, so let's take stock. The
position is objectively level but with plenty of play for both sides, so
overall Black should be very happy with the result of the opening. As opposed
to the pawn on e6, White's central pawn on d4 gives her a little more space
but is also a target for the black pieces. Black can increase the pressure
with ...Bg4 and putting a rook on the d-file, though she should be careful of
playing ...Bd6 if White can respond with Ne4. -- From White's perspective, she
would like to throw in a prophylactic h2-h3 to stop the pin on the Nf3.
However, it is a little time-consuming and Black can usually respond with a
quick ...Bf6 and put pressure on the centre. White's mercurial bishop on b3
can prove to be the hero or the villain, depending on whether or not it can
eventually see open space on the a2-g8 diagonal. Black should keep an eye out
for a d4-d5 push, usually by playing either ...Nc6-a5xb3, or by flicking in ...
