Devotees of this gambit are often zealous to the extent that nothing can
persuade them of its unsoundness, and who are we to judge such dogmatism about
a dubious defence? In fact, despite most opening texts dismissing 2 d4 with
barely a mention, the gambit can be tricky to face over the board,
particularly against a bloodthirsty opponent who knows the theory back to
front. What's more, it occurs in club chess, and especially blitz, far more
often than you might expect. Consequently, I have decided to spend a bit of
time shoring up Black's repertoire, and I recommend you do the same. But make
no mistake: this gambit is completely unsound, and with good preparation Black
can be hopeful of coming out of the opening with at least a slight advantage
and likely much more than that.} Bf5 {There are several ways of playing
against the BDG that are more than satisfactory for Black, but in my opinion
