1. e4 d5 2. e5 $6 {Strangely enough, this move is more common than 2 d4. I
suspect its popularity comes from players from the white side who are
surprised by 1...d5 and seek to get out of the well-trodden paths as quickly
as possible. As is so often the case, such deviations come at a cost. White
invites a transposition to the Advance Variations of the French (2...e6) or
Caro-Kann (2...c6) defences. However, Black can strive for improved versions
of both openings. Even nicer is the fact that she doesn't need to know any
particular theoretical variations or be aware of specific tricks in order to
obtain a healthy position.} c5 {My favourite reply,} ({but there are equally
promising alternatives:} 2... Bf5 {aims for a superior version of the
Caro-Kann, where Black will achieve ...c7-c5 in one move instead of two and
has already equalized.}) (2... d4 $5 {is also a very good response. Black
immediately quells any ambitions White might have had of transposing into a
more orthodox opening. Without the possibility of a routine centre by playing
d2-d4 herself, White must try to prop up the e5-pawn by other means. In the
ensuing positions with this unusual pawn structure, Black usually secures a
space advantage and easy development. One example of this went} 3. Nf3 c5 4.
Bc4 e6 5. O-O Ne7 6. d3 Ng6 $1 {(preventing Bf4)} 7. Re1 Nc6 8. Qe2 b6 9. Bb5
Bb7 {and Black had built up an excellent position in Ch.Kr√ºger-C.M√ºller,
German League 1992. Note that White's e5-pawn is a lot less secure than the d4
bastion - this is the key advantage for Black of the asymmetrical formations.
Unfortunately, after} 10. Ng5 $5 {, Black took the bait and fell for} Be7 ({
instead,} 10... Qc7 {would have left Black with a clear advantage}) 11. Nxf7
Kxf7 12. Qf3+ {and White won a pawn}) 3. c3 (3. f4 Nc6 4. Nf3 Bg4 $1 {
demonstrates the key advantage of having a French-like structure with the
e-pawn back home. Then} 5. c3 ({after} 5. Bb5 e6 6. O-O Nge7 7. h3 Bxf3 8. Qxf3
Nf5 {, Black has a dream French Defence}) 5... e6 6. Bb5 Nge7 7. O-O a6 8. Ba4
{was already good for Black in Pa.Dimitrov-G.A.Szabo, Sunny Beach 2009, and
here} b5 9. Bc2 d4 $1 {was the most accurate way to press home the advantage.})
3... Nc6 (3... c4 $5 {is a more unusual approach. After} 4. d4 cxd3 5. Bxd3 Nc6
6. f4 Nh6 7. Nd2 Bf5 {, Black had equalized with seeming ease and went on
score to a comfortable victory in A.Shirshova-E.Alekseev, Uljanovsk 2009
(that's not GM Alekseev, by the way).}) 4. d4 {Again inviting a transposition
to a French should Black continue 4...e6. It's perhaps worth noting that the
Advance French is considered perfectly acceptable for Black from a theoretical
perspective, but she should certainly prefer taking advantage of our
Scandinavian move-order.} ({Instead,} 4. f4 d4 {gives Black a structural
advantage not dissimilar to the lines analysed after 2...d4, and} 5. d3 f6 6.
exf6 $6 exf6 7. Nf3 Bd6 8. Be2 Nh6 9. h3 O-O {was clearly better for Black in
upsss (2000)-D.Smerdon, Internet 2013.}) 4... Bf5 $1 5. Nf3 e6 {After teasing
each other with transpositional dance moves, the waltz has led us again to a
nice French, or a souped-up Caro-Kann, depending on your imagination. One
thing is clear: Black is doing very well.} ({For example,} 5... e6 6. Bb5 Qb6
7. Bxc6+ bxc6 {was already a bit better for Black in M.Vandervorst-Vl.Georgiev,
La Fere 2012 (in which this position arose via a c2-c3 Sicilian).}) (5... -- {
Section Five - Conclusion: White should be wary of trying to dodge a
theoretical debate with these sidelines. Black's first move, 1...d5, is in a
sense her most ambitious answer to 1...e4, as it immediately seeks to gain
superiority in space and in the centre. Should White not take up the challenge
with one of the replies from the previous sections, then Black's ambition is
rewarded with at least equality from the opening, and in many cases a rapid
advantage. --- Of White's options in this section, only 2 exd5 Nf6 3 Nc3 can
be considered fully sound. You will face this reasonably often in practice,
though White can lay no claim to an advantage - the resulting positions are
equal, while retaining sufficient imbalance that all results are possible.
Against White's other choices at move two, the news is even better: you should
now feel confident to press for the full point straight from the word go!}) *

