{Wow, that was a long book. And you made it all the way to the end - well
done! It has been a joy to write, but it turned out to be a much bigger book
than I expected. There are three reasons for this.} 1. -- (1. -- {Firstly, as
I wrote each chapter, I discovered many new ideas, for both sides, that have
never before been played or published. This is evident from the high number of
novelties scattered throughout the chapters, and which any reader of a new
opening book should be happy to see. I wish you many quick and effortless
points on account of these discoveries!}) (1. -- {Secondly, I wanted to make
sure that all lines were covered, even those that I don't personally believe
are very important. This meant going deep into branches that objectively
aren't threatening, but may well crop up more often than they ought to in
practice. In particular, I have placed extra focus on variations that occur
with high frequency, such as the Wuss and the surprisingly common 3 Nc3 in
Section Five.}) (1. -- {And finally, seeing as this is the first comprehensive
repertoire project to focus on 3...Bg4, I wanted the book to stand the test of
time. There will undoubtedly be corrections and improvements on this work in
the future as chess computers grow stronger, and so I have been as thorough as
I possibly can, double- and triple-checking the analysis with multiple engines.
Despite my best efforts, some lines in this book will inevitably be cast as
dubious by authors and theoreticians at some point or another, which is why I
have offered alternative lines for Black in most chapters. --- It may yet come
to pass that our favourite weapon is eventually banished to the backwaters of
refuted openings; but even if such a tragedy does occur, I sincerely hope that
this book provides you with a hefty double-dose of pleasurable reading and
sparkling victories for many years to come.}) *
